Yes, serving your Svelte app using a server will work with Supabase. Supabase is a client-side library that communicates with the Supabase backend via API calls. As long as your app can make HTTP requests, it can interact with Supabase.

When you serve your Svelte app on a server, your app's static files are delivered to the browser, and the browser runs your JavaScript code, including the Supabase client. This means that your app can communicate with the Supabase backend, regardless of which server you use to serve your app's static files.

To ensure that your app works correctly with Supabase, make sure you have initialized the Supabase client with the correct API keys and endpoint URL. These values can be found in your Supabase project dashboard.

Here's an example of how to initialize the Supabase client in your app (e.g., in `src/lib/supabase.js`):
```javascript
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js';

const SUPABASE_URL = 'your-supabase-url';
const SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = 'your-supabase-anon-key';

const supabase = createClient(SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_ANON_KEY);

export default supabase;
```
Replace `'your-supabase-url'` and `'your-supabase-anon-key'` with the values from your Supabase project dashboard. With the client correctly configured, your Svelte app will be able to interact with Supabase when served from a server.
